# cgm module placement and boundaries

## Default homes for new code

| Kind of code | Where it goes |
|--------------|---------------|
| General utilities (paths, math, P4, file IO, Maya cmds without meta) | **`cgm/core/lib/`** — extend an existing `*_utils.py` or add a new module (e.g. `lib/perforce.py`) |
| Meta, blocks, Scene, rig build logic | **`cgm/core/mrs/`**, **`cgm/core/rig/`**, and **`mrs/lib/`** |
| Artist tool windows / shelves | **`cgm/core/tools/`** (+ **`tools/lib/`** for shared UI chunks) |
| Truly global cross-cutting helpers (logging, callbacks) | **`cgm/core/cgm_General.py`** — sparingly; prefer **`lib/`** for new feature logic |

Match import style of nearby callers (e.g. `import cgm.core.lib.path_utils as PATHUTIL`).

## Do not modify vendored / out-of-scope trees

- **`cgm/lib/zoo/`** (zooPy) — not ours: **no edits**, **no wiring cgm.core through it**.
- **`Red9/`** (vendored Red9 core / docs; Pro Pack if present on disk) — **do not modify without explicit user clearance**, including when fixing bugs. Default: fix or work around in **`cgm/core/`** (usually **`lib/`**, **`mrs/`**, **`tools/`**). If a bug truly lives in Red9, **ask first** before editing Red9 files.
- Useful vendored patterns → **reimplement or wrap under `cgm/core/lib/`**, not import/patch upstream.

## Keep modules focused

- Do not bolt unrelated features onto a module because it is already imported (P4 belongs in **`lib/perforce.py`**, not `cgm_General` or zooPy).
- **Callers** (`Scene.py`, `bakeAndPrep.py`, …) stay thin: import a **`lib/`** helper, orchestrate, return.
- Before extending a large file, search **`cgm/core/lib/`** and **`mrs/lib/`** for an existing helper.

